The title should be: "Who contributed to the invention of the current state-of-the-art A.I. algorithms". A.I. is a large and ambiguous term. It is a multi-disciplinary field, where the heart of its theory is driven from math, neuroscience, and computer science fields. In addition, Neural Networks are a subset of algorithms in the machine learning area, where the aim is to design models that learn from data, using many optimizations and engineering methods. The video is good, however, I would be cautious when making such claims. Nonetheless, the scientists mentioned in the video are brilliant, and their determination is what drove A.I to its current status.

Great video, Chris.  And great to chat with you a few days ago.  To those that are confused about all the backlash the Manjaro team got over this, my video and all the community responses regarding this decision by Manjaro might seem like overreactions to those that are not invested in the politics of FOSS (or those not aware of such politics).  But so be it.  The Linux community called out these guys for pushing proprietary trialware, and the Linux community got them to change their minds.   The FOSS zealots (I include myself among them) did this not for ourselves but FOR ALL LINUX USERS, even those do not understand or agree with our position.  The moment we start allowing pre-installed proprietary trialware to become the norm, well...we might as well be running Windows then.  Thank you, Linux community!  And thank you, Manjaro team!  I do hope the folks at Manjaro start understanding the vital role they play in the free and open source software movement, and never shirk their responsibility in said movement.

HOW DARE THEY USE CLOSED SOURCE SOFTWARE?!  THIS IS MADNESS!!!  [Goes and installs Steam, emulates some Windows-only games, plays a few retro ROMs, then uses Chrome to sign a petition to get Adobe to port CC to Linux, and finally logs into Facebook to tell everyone how into FOSS I am]
Mac Users:  Learning Windows is too hard Windows Users:  Learning Linux is too hard 30% of US Adults:  Learning to SET THE MICROWAVE CLOCK is too hard

I run Manjaro on my laptop. It's a great distro. I think this situation could have been handled better, but the reaction to it was over the top and unwarranted.  I take particular offense at people calling proprietary software "garbage". I have been a developer on and off for decades. I have written proprietary software for clients. I work hard to keep my skills current and to produce the best program possible. My work isn't "garbage" because I am paid for it, or because you can't examine my code (not that any of you do), and FOSS is not superior because it is free. When a bug turns up in a proprietary program, it has to be fixed, and it has to be fixed NOW. If a bug turns up in a FOSS program, oh well. Maybe you'll be lucky and it will be fixed in the next release. Or maybe the bug will remain unfixed for years despite repeated reports and requests from users. Try running a business that way. This "holier than thou" attitude is bullshit.  I run MS Office in a Windows VM under Linux. I have certain documents set up to print a certain way. If I open those documents in Libre Office and print them, they do not look the same. The positioning is off. That's a problem. If this alternative office suite really works better than Libre Office for the things I need done, I will consider purchasing it, and I will be very appreciative to the Manjaro team for bringing it to my attention. If they get financial benefits from the arrangement, great. They deserve to be paid for their work, and begging for donations from people only goes so far.

Your point about beautiful math being engaging is one I've been making for YEARS. Every time we had a "problem solving" session in my ordinary drone of a high school math class, if the problem was interesting, challenging, aesthetic, and cool for its own sake, people were more engaged than any amount of the teacher telling us how useful the math we were learning would be for our careers.  The students who would otherwise play on their phones or read books or otherwise zone out were actively offering insights, asking questions, and trying new creative ways to solve whatever puzzle was posed. To make math fun and engaging, it doesn't need to be useful for our careers and I don't quite understand why, when I tell people I study math, they ask what I'm going to use it for or why I find it interesting. No one asks that to artists, musicians, creative writing majors, etc. I'm really glad Grant is making this message spread farther than I ever could.

After watching your first video, I ended up drawing a "mock" neural  network up on paper that would work on a 3x3 grid (after all what else are you supposed to do during a boring lecture class?). Later that evening and the next one, I tried to program the same function taking PNGs as inputs and definitions of the neurons and it honestly was only a little more rewarding.
